    <stitle>STEERING COLUMN ASSEMBLY, TILT/TELESCOPING - 2000, 4000, 8000 - UNIVERSAL JOINTS</stitle>
    <svcsection/>
    <svcsubsec>
        <title>UNIVERSAL JOINTS</title>
        <svcsubsecinfo>
            <para>The universal joint at the upper end of the drive shaft can be serviced without removing the steering
                column from the vehicle.
            </para>
            <para>Once the shaft and universal joints are removed from the vehicle or steering column, the procedure for
                servicing the universal joints is as follows.
            </para>
            <specpara>
                <caution>
                    <para>Do not damage bearing surfaces. Doing so may inhibit steering performance.</para>
                </caution>
            </specpara>
        </svcsubsecinfo>
        <svcproc svcproctype="disassemble" graphiccount="3">
            <title>DISASSEMBLE</title>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Place universal joint in vise as shown in
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0501204">Figure 4</hotlnk>. Remove snap ring fitting in grooves of the spider
                    bearings which locate them on the inside of the yokes. To remove snap rings, place a screwdriver
                    against an end of the snap ring and push.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f0501204" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g0501204" filename="../figg05/G0501204.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 4. Place Universal Joint in Vise</caption>
                <calloutgroup>
                    <callout1>1.BEARING</callout1>
                    <callout1>2. YOKE</callout1>
                    <callout1>3. SPIDER</callout1>
                    <callout1>4. SNAP RING</callout1>
                </calloutgroup>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Place shaft assembly in vise with one yoke resting on the vise and the other yoke
                    suspended with the bearing to be removed facing down (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0501205">Figure 5</hotlnk>). Tap yoke beside bearing to be removed; bearing should
                    walk out of the yoke.
                </para>
                <figure id="f0501205" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g0501205" filename="../figg05/G0501205.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 5. Removing Bearings</caption>
                    <calloutgroup>
                        <callout1>1. BEARING</callout1>
                        <callout1>2. YOKE</callout1>
                    </calloutgroup>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">If the bearing does not come completely out, clamp bearing in vise. Use copper jaw
                    covers on vise. Strike the yoke with a soft hammer and drive the yoke away from the bearing as shown
                    in
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0501206">Figure 6</hotlnk>.
                </para>
                <figure id="f0501206" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g0501206" filename="../figg05/G0501206.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 6. Drive Yoke Away From Bearing</caption>
                    <calloutgroup>
                        <callout1>1. YOKE</callout1>
                        <callout1>2. BEARING</callout1>
                    </calloutgroup>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">With the bearings removed, the spider can be easily removed from the yoke.</para>
            </step1>
        </svcproc>
    </svcsubsec>
